📊 Distribution Visualizer – Full Project Description

The Distribution Visualizer is an interactive data analytics application built using Python that enables users to explore and understand different
statistical distributions through dynamic visualizations. The project focuses on simplifying complex statistical concepts by providing real-time graphical
representations of probability distributions such as Normal, Binomial, Poisson, and Uniform.

The application is developed using a modular architecture, where the core distribution logic is implemented using libraries like NumPy and SciPy,
while visualization is handled through Matplotlib. A user-friendly interface is built using Streamlit, allowing users to interact with the application
via sliders and controls to adjust parameters such as mean, standard deviation, probability, and number of trials.

As users modify these parameters, the application dynamically updates plots including Probability Density Functions (PDF) and
Probability Mass Functions (PMF), helping them observe how distributions change in real time. This makes the tool especially useful for
exploratory data analysis (EDA), statistical learning, and educational purposes.

Additionally, the project demonstrates key data analytics skills such as data visualization, statistical modeling, and interactive

dashboard development. The codebase follows clean and modular design principles by separating logic into reusable components, improving maintainability and scalability.

Future enhancements include adding real-world dataset support, comparative analysis between multiple distributions, and deployment as a web-based analytics dashboard.
